{With no 4-card Major suit you respond 2\D to partner's Stayman bid. Partner now bids 2NT.  

With no 4-card Major suit you respond 2\D to partner's Stayman bid. Partner now bids 2NT. 

With a full 17 points you accept partner's game invitation and bid 3NT.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \S6 on which East plays the \SQ.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 2 : \D = 2 : \C = 1 :: Total = 6

You need 3 more tricks, obviously coming from the \C suit.

But the burning question right now is what do you do at trick one. Do you win or hold up? 

You should assume that West holds the \SK.

If you take the \SA right now your \S J 5 will provide a second stopper if it is West who gets the lead. However, if East gets the lead he will play through your holding and you may lose 4 \S tricks.

If you hold up you can expect East to play another \S through your \S A J and West will then establish the suit. However, in doing so he will remove any \S held by East.

The answer key lies in the \C suit. You will be finessing through West, so East is the only defender who can get the lead in \Cs. Therefore you must hold up on \Ss until the third round.

If you win the first \S East will play a \S through your \S J 5 when he wins the \CK. West will then swamp you with \Ss.

But, if you hold up your \SA until the third round, East will have no \S left when he wins the \CK.}
[Play "W"]S6

